    en: "A quitclaim deed transfers whatever interest one person has in real estate to another person, with no promise that the title is good. New York Real Property Law § 258 sets the standard form. Quitclaim deeds are commonly used to add a spouse to a deed, remove an ex-spouse after divorce, transfer property between family members, place property into a trust, or correct a prior recording error. The grantor signs and acknowledges the deed before a notary, and the deed is recorded at the County Clerk's office. NY transfer tax and a real property transfer report (RP-5217) generally apply, with limited family-transfer exemptions."
